          "body": "Romans 13:13-14 is the text Augustine read in the garden at Milan in AD 386. *Tolle, lege* — take up and read. He opened to these verses and wrote in the *Confessions* (VIII.12.29) that he read no further: *instantly, as the sentence ended, by a light, as it were, of serenity infused into my heart, all the darkness of doubt vanished away*. The historical detail matters because it reveals what this chapter *does*. It is not abstract ethics; it is the gospel applied to the body, the calendar, and the wardrobe. The chapter that began with submission to the state ends with submission to the morning. The believer who has put on Christ has nothing left to hide in the dark — because the day has come."
